UML:TaggedValue.value: This package defines the requirements of the FSDF PlaceNames Theme Conceptual model

INSPIRE Annex I data specification for "Geographic Names" defines a model for NamedPlace which has - one InspireID - one or more names - one geometry - one or more type classifiers - optionally, an indication of the map scales (resolution) for which the feature should be viewed - optionally, links to related feature instances included in other data themes - lifecycle information The 'GeographicName' datatype supports a range of linguistic and localization propeties. This model is not related in any explicit way to the ISO standards. However, it does introduce the notion that a NamedPlace (or Gazetteer entry) provides a simplified view of feature(s) that appear with additional properties in a thematic dataset. This places the gazetteer as a lowest common denominator index of identified features, the details of which may be expressed in more specialized datasets. Since FSDF proposes a comprehensive suite of datamodels, this requirement is useful and should be reflected in the FSDF Gazetteer model.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Implementable as lossless common data transfer

ISO 19112 "Spatial Referencing by Identifier" standardizes a model for Gazetteer information, based on the assumption that a LocationInstance has: - one preferred Identifier - a competent adminstrator - a location-type (i.e. feature type) that classifies the location instance - a spatial extent, or a representative point location, or both - optionally, a temporal extent (period of validity) - optionally, multiple alternative identifiers or names by which it is known and is included in one or more Gazetteers.
This basic set of requirements serves as a checklist that any conformant Gazetteer implementation must satisfy.
The FSDF Place Names model should support all requirements from ISO 19112.
The mapping-model should indicate how each of the named classes, attributes and association roles from ISO 19112 are realised in FSDF Gazetteer.

UML:ClassifierRole.name: Link with FSDF thematic models and data products

UML:TaggedValue.value: SIRF defines a CommonGazetteer model, with a GazetteerEntry class which is inspired by the ISO 19112 requirements, with key properties: - URI Identifier - optional preferred name - a link to one source feature - a location-type (i.e. feature-type) that classifies the GazetteerEntry - a spatial extent, or a representative point location, or both - optional multiple alternate names and is part of a single gazetteer. The Name class supports classification of the name by status and type. Links to related features and classifiers (country, source-type, location-type) use URIs that are required to conform to the requirements of a LID. This is because SIRF is particularly concerned with deployment in a persistent linked-data framework. The FSDF Place Names model should consider whethr any of these specific requirements apply. The mapping-model should record the correspondences where appropriate.

A GML implementation of ISO 19112 is used in the Gazetteer Profile of WFS ("WFS-G") to provide a standard Gazetteer service interface to which a WFS client can connect. The GML implementation closely follows the ISO 19112 conceptual schema, with minor changes due to XML Schema limitations. A UML model can be reverse engineered from the GML schema, providing a convenient representation of the standard WFS-G gazetteer payload. The CGNA has deployed a WFS-G Gazetteer service for Australia, managed and hosted by GA. The payload of the WFS-G deployed by CGNA should be understood as an implementation of the FSDF Place Names model. The mapping model should indicate how the mandatory and optional classes, attributes and association roles from FSDF Gazetteer are implemented in WFS-G.

A joint W3C/OGC actiivty is developing a Point Of Interest (POI) standard. POI is a slightly different use-case from Gazetteer, (i) geometry is limited to points (ii) no requirement for any particular authorization (such as Gazetting) (iii) there may be some free-form descriptive information about the POI included. The POI representation is generally simpler than most other models, and may be considered a minimal 'view'. The FSDF Gazetteer model needs to be mapped to W3C POI as a potential implementation.

The CGNA WFS-G Gazetteer service may provide input to a data-store or transient representation structured according to the FSDF Gazetteer model.
The WFS-G --> FSDF Gazetteer mapping must provide for lossless capture of all WFS-G classes, attributes and association roles.

The UML profile must support generation of GML and OWL representations.
In practice, this means that it should use the ISO 19103 UML profile, and ISO 19136 stereotypes and tagged values.
